I've implemented issue 02 end-to-end:

**What was built** (all zero-runtime-dependency, stdlib only):
- `git_ops.py`: added `has_commits`, `is_clean` (precondition checks) and `branch_exists`, `remove_worktree`, `delete_branch` (scoped cleanup primitives)
- `runner.py`: `run_task` now refuses non-git, no-commit, or dirty targets *before* creating any State Dir side effects
- `runs.py` (new): read-only Run listing/lookup (`list_runs`, `load_run_metadata`)
- `views.py` (new): plain-text rendering for `status` and `list`
- `cleanup.py` (new): `clean_run`/`clean_all`, scoped strictly to the run's worktree, its `factory/<run-id>` branch, and its State Dir entry
- `cli.py`: new `status`, `list`, `clean <run-id>|--all` subcommands
- `tests/test_isolation_preconditions_cleanup.py` (new): end-to-end tests against real temp git repos covering every acceptance criterion, including a forced Run-ID collision test

**Blocker:** same as issue 01 — this AFK session's Bash tool refuses every mutating/interpreter-invoking command (`python3 -m pytest`, etc.) with no human to approve, so I couldn't execute the test suite. I verified the code by careful manual trace-through instead (git command semantics, ordering, `git branch --list` prefix handling) and documented this in the issue's Comments, with the status set to `needs-info` pending a test run once the sandbox/approval constraint is lifted.
